    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You've hit the nail on the head! When the boundary layer on the wing becomes too thick or turbulent, it can indeed ruin the lift. This is because a thicker boundary layer can cause the airflow over the wing to separate from the surface, leading to a sudden loss of lift. This phenomenon is known as a stall. It's like when the smooth, orderly flow of air is disrupted, and the wing can't \"see\" the air anymore, causing it to lose its ability to lift the plane. Pilots need to be careful to avoid situations that might cause the boundary layer to become too thick, like flying too close to the ground or at too high an angle of attack. It's a delicate balance, but when it's right, the wing can soar through the skies with ease.",
